    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-05-02T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-05-02T23:00:00-05:00" n="158"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94119/418: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-03T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 3, 1938—noon.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 3—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>232. Department’s 124, April 13, 7 p.m.<note n="37" xml:id="d158fn37">Not
                        printed.</note> Counselor [of] British Embassy informed me today in the
                    course of a conversation that question of mediation had been recently canvassed
                    by the British Government, but that conclusion had been reached that mediation
                    was out of the question as there was no basis upon which mediation could be
                    profitably offered to either side.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
